n":{"1032–2 Nov 1083":"1032–2 November 1083","1032–1083":"1032–1083","1020–1100":"1020–1100","1045–1103":"1045–1103","1050–1113":"1050–1113","–Female":"Deceased","1006–1082":"1006–1082","1010–Female":"1010–Deceased","about 1050":"about 1050","about 1082":"about 1082","1032":"1032","1010":"1010","1020":"1020","1050":"1050","1083":"1083","1082":"1082","1006":"1006","1103":"1103","1113":"1113","1045":"1045","1100":"1100","2 Nov 1083":"2 November 1083","about 1032":"about 1032","about 1045":"about 1045","Ewias, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ewias, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Capelle-les-Grands, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Capelle-les-Grands, Eure, Normandy, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud de Ingelrica was born in 1032, in Capelle-les-Grands, Eure, Normandy, France, her father, Earl Of Essex Ingelric Saxon Of England, was 27 and her mother, Adelaide of France, was 23. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Ranulph De Peverel. She died on 2 November 1083, in her hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1032–2 Nov 1083":"1032–2. november 1083","1032–1083":"1032–1083","1020–1100":"1020–1100","1045–1103":"1045–1103","1050–1113":"1050–1113","–Female":"Surnud","1006–1082":"1006–1082","1010–Female":"1010–Surnud","about 1050":"umbes 1050","about 1082":"umbes 1082","1032":"1032","1010":"1010","1020":"1020","1050":"1050","1083":"1083","1082":"1082","1006":"1006","1103":"1103","1113":"1113","1045":"1045","1100":"1100","2 Nov 1083":"2. november 1083","about 1032":"umbes 1032","about 1045":"umbes 1045","Ewias, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ewias, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Capelle-les-Grands, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Capelle-les-Grands, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1032–2 Nov 1083":"1032–2. marraskuuta 1083","1032–1083":"1032–1083","1020–1100":"1020–1100","1045–1103":"1045–1103","1050–1113":"1050–1113","–Female":"Kuollut","1006–1082":"1006–1082","1010–Female":"1010–Kuollut","about 1050":"noin 1050","about